entry.title: Properly update the ICB when shrinking print contents.
entry.content:
Be more consistent about this. Scaling specified by the print preview UI

was taken into account, but scaling caused by internal page scaling (to

avoid / reduce inline overflow) was not.



The initial containing block isn't used for a lot of things when

printing, since each page defines a containing block. However, for

out-of-flow positioned boxes and things like vw and vh units, it

matters.



Bug: 1485819

entry.title: Honor @page orientation when fitting to page size.
entry.content:
If an actual printer is selected (i.e. not PDF), and CSS margins are to

be honored (choosing "default" margins in the print preview UI), @page

sizes are honored, except that everything is scaled down to fit on

paper. Make sure that we honor any implicit or explicit @page

orientation, rather than scaling down a landscape page so much it will

fit in portrait orientation.



This regressed with crrev.com/1195546, since the now-gone

EnsureOrientationMatches() function also played a role when fitting to

page, not just when ignoring page size completely (i.e. non-default

margins + real printer).



Bug: 1485727

entry.title: [IP Protection] Better handle OAuth token error events
entry.content:
This CL addresses two issues:

- Fetching the OAuth token can fail because of transient errors and

permanent errors, and we were treating both of those as permanent.

We now distinguish between the two and handle them more

appropriately.



- For workspace accounts, fetching the OAuth token can encounter

permanent failures because the user needs to log in again, and to

recover from this we need to listen for changes to the refresh

token state instead of just listening for primary account change

events.

entry.title: [GridNG] Omit trailing default grid-area and grid shorthand values
entry.content:
Per https://drafts.csswg.org/cssom/#serializing-css-values "If component

values can be omitted or replaced with a shorter representation without

changing the meaning of the value, omit/replace them."



This means that trailing `auto` values can be dropped from

`grid-area` definitions, and `none` can also be dropped from computed

styles for grid shorthands. For this, I determine the end index by

iterating backwards. The same approach was taken for CSSOM and shorthand

computed style, although shorthand skips both `auto` and `none`.



This also updates numerous `fast/` test expectations that were

incorrect. I added a TODO for a follow-up that I'll do next, which is

to omit the second if it's identical to the first.

entry.title: AW docs: clarify instructions for exposing flags
entry.content:
No change to policy. The goal of this CL is not to change the existing

flag policy, but rather to provide clearer guidance based on feedback

we've received and data about how developers actually expose their

flags:



* Provide guidance on autogenerated constants. Developers are still

allowed to use string literals, but data shows the majority of CLs use

constants (only 5/180 flags use strings, the rest use constants).

* Add an optional step for the description, and emphasize this is

optional. Descriptions are also popular (only 10/180 flags don't have

descriptions).

* Remind the developer that any chromium committer can approve changes.

Most folks have figured this out from the OWNERS file, but it doesn't

hurt to clarify.

* Remind the developer that a flag exemption is no longer needed once

the flag is exposed. The goal here is to avoid some unnecessary code

reviews on the internal Finch CL.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix Overflow Menu dragged destinations hiding and not reappearing
entry.content:
I believe the root cause of this bug is that iOS 16 does not natively

support observing optional ObservableObjects. So initially the code just

used the drag handler directly. However, when the drag ends, this does

not trigger the destination list view to re-create itself, so the

dragged item stays hidden.



This CL adds a wrapper container that just forwards any changes in the

optional child on. This could probably be a more generic class, but

that would be pretty complex and this is much simpler. Also, iOS 17

introduces Observable, which should also fix this problem.

entry.title: Implement experiment to not PreReadFile(chrome.dll) in non-browsers
entry.content:
Context for this change is Catan's investigation into (primarily GPU)

startup performance. We believe that this change will reduce contention

by not pulling the entirety of chrome.dll into physical memory when each

process will only use its own small subset of the DLL, with the

hypothesis that this will not slow process startup because the browser

process has already PreRead the file into memory (for earlier processes)

and the sections which are used during execution are kept in physical

memory regardless (for later processes).

entry.title: [APS] Post clearance of hover state on tab strip down event
entry.content:
Currently, TabStripEventHandler#onDown() attempts to clear any

persisting tab hover state when a down event is received on the strip; a

down event is always received before a subsequent click/drag/long

press/fling etc. However, during a tab close button click, the clearance

does not take effect possibly due to tab closure animations.



This CL introduces a PostTask to reasonably delay hover state clearance

in onDown() as a best effort for the clearance to take effect after any

animations triggered due to the down event have ended. This would mean

that showing the hover card for a tab that is possibly moved to the

same time.

hard to reproduce.

entry.title: May break before float, but still fit subsequent in-flow content.
entry.content:
It is possible for a float to be pushed to the next fragmentainer, while

still fitting subsequent in-flow content in the current fragmentainer.

Therefore, keep looking for content inside a culled inline, even if

we've found a float that belongs in a later fragmentainer.



This is similar to how a float may be pushed below the current line if

it doesn't fit beside it, while still laying out items that come after

it DOM-tree-wise, on the same line. A float may be pushed to the next

fragmentainer if it doesn't fit in the current one. But there may still

be room for plenty of in-flow lines in the current fragmentainer.

entry.title: [omnibox] Break strings on numbers.
entry.content:
Previously, when breaking strings into words, providers broke on

whitespace and symbols.



Providers used `TailoredWordBreakIterator` a child of

`base::i18n::BreakIterator`, because the latter did not break on

underscores.



This CL makes `TailoredWordBreakIterator` also break on numbers.



Given the string: `aaa bbb*ccc_ddd555fff`



`BreakIterator` produces:

`aaa, , bbb, *, ccc_ddd555fff`



`TailoredWordBreakIterator` before this CL produced:

`aaa, , bbb, *, ccc, _, ddd555fff`



`TailoredWordBreakIterator` with this CL produces:

`aaa, , bbb, *, ccc, _, ddd, 555, fff`



This fixes cases where the input 'stable 117' would not match suggestion

text 'stable m117' which was causing HQP instability.



One downside is that for shortcuts, inputs like 'a' will expand to

'aaaa' instead of aaaa1111'. This is a minimal risk since shortcut

expands appends at least 3 chars before expanding to the next word

break.

entry.title: Don't remove nodes from ResourceContext registries until they're deleted
entry.content:
Stores WeakPtr's to the nodes and removes them from the registry when

the WeakPtr is invalidated, instead of in OnBefore*NodeRemoved(). This

allows clients of the registry to look up a node that's about to be

removed from the graph even if the registry handles the notification

before the client does.



This simplifies ResourceContext lookups in CPUMeasurementMonitor.



R=anthonyvd
